Foot & mouth disease - UK (41) 20010407.0688
[It should be immediately noted that The Telegraph is traditionally a
Conservative paper. The following reports should be read with that in mind.
- Mod.MHJ
[1
Date: 6 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Telegraph [edited
<http://www.telegraph.co.uk:80/et?ac=002559874442765&rtmo=QwkOkaaR&atmo=tttttttd&pg=/et/01/4/6/nfnm06.html>

Fatal delay over foot and mouth
----------------------------------------------
[It is claimed that Ministers and officials at first ignored independent
epidemiologists who offered their help shortly after the outbreak was
announced and who could have warned that the initial policy was allowing
the disease to spiral out of control. The serious shortcomings in the
ministry's handling of foot and mouth almost certainly played a significant
role in the outbreak developing into a national crisis. The decision to
play down the advice of the scientists went directly against the report of
the inquiry into the 1967-68 outbreak which said epidemiologists had to be
on standby to study the outbreak "from the start".
The Government also ignored an Army report into the 1967-68 crisis which
warned that even in the event of a small outbreak, the Army should be
brought in immediately "to ensure it did not develop into a major problem".
The report, unearthed by The Telegraph in the Public Record Office, said
Maff was simply incapable of masterminding an operation to control the
spread of the disease. It criticized the use of veterinary surgeons to
organize the operation, a key feature of the current outbreak. By the time
the Army was first called in, 12 days into the 1967 crisis, "there was
already a large backlog of carcasses awaiting destruction, and of farms
awaiting disinfection" and Maff was unable to cope. Once the Army were
called in to assist there was a rapid improvement in the control and
organization of all facilities. "It became possible to establish a proper
system of operational control." It concluded: "In a national emergency of
this nature, the earlier the military can be called in the better." Maff
agreed at the time that the Army should be called in immediately in the
event of any future occurrence of the disease, but it was not until a month
into the current outbreak that the troops were called in.
The external scientists, from Imperial College and Edinburgh University,
were only called in on 6 Mar [2001 -- 2 weeks after the epidemic began. It
was not until a month after the start of the outbreak that the Government
acted on their advice to speed up the cull. By 16 Mar [2001, Jim
Scudamore, Chief Veterinary Officer, was being told by the external
epidemiologists and Maff's own scientists that the disease was out of control.
Despite clear indications that current control measures were not working --
because of an average delay of 3 or so days between diagnosis and slaughter
-- there was no explicit move to cut the time to slaughter. A Maff
spokesman said this was consistent with what was known at the time, though
he admitted they could not cope with the demands of slaughter.
The Edinburgh and Imperial teams predicted that the delays would mean a
doubling of the epidemic every 8 or so days. It was not until 23 Mar
[2001, a week after the initial warning, that Prof David King, the
Government's chief scientist, warned that drastic action was necessary to
reduce the delay. This would suggest that the initial failure to react
doubled the size of the epidemic. One of the scientists involved commented
that the information provided that day "was not news to them [Maff".
Because of lack of resources, "they just did not think they could do
anything about it". There was a "defeatist attitude", despite the knowledge
by many in the ministry that the battle against the disease was being lost.
The realization that more had to be done had to wait until a joint meeting
between Maff and the Food Standards Agency on 21 Mar [2001. At the
meeting, teams at Imperial College, London, Cambridge and Edinburgh
universities and the Government's Veterinary Laboratories Agency gave
firmer predictions. Notable among these was that as many as 400 cases would
be reported per day by the end of June, requiring the slaughter of half of
Britain's livestock, unless firmer controls were put in place. It was
publicly admitted that the disease was out of control in a statement
released by Maff on 23 Mar.
But it was Prof King who, when he heard the dire predictions at the
meeting, "ran with them", calling for firm time-to-slaughter policies, said
one of those present. It was only then that Tony Blair appreciated the
seriousness of the epidemic. Before flying to Stockholm for an EU summit on
the evening of 22 Mar, he visited the worst hit area of Cumbria. The Prime
Minister was shocked by the scale of the slaughter and by the report from
the epidemiologists, which he read on the flight. He then decided to take
personal control of the Government's efforts to control the epidemic and
order a major upgrading of the Army's role.
[Byline: Roger Highfield, Michael Smith and David Brown
--
