[2
Date: 7 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Telegraph [edited
<http://www.telegraph.co.uk:80/et?ac=002559874442765&rtmo=aCX9469J&atmo=tttttttd&pg=/et/01/4/7/nfnm107.html>
Ministers deny "series of errors" [edited
-----------------------------------------------
Ministers yesterday rejected claims that they had made a series of serious
errors in their handling of the foot and mouth crisis. As the Tories said
the Army should have been brought in sooner, Joyce Quin, an agriculture
minister, dismissed allegations that Government delays had led to a
near-doubling in the extent of the epidemic.
Speaking on Radio 4's Today programme, Ms Quin said the Army was not
sidelined during the early days of the outbreak. "There was contact between
ministers in Maff and the Ministry of Defence on 20 Feb 2001, the day the
outbreak was first suspected, in order to say 'We may have a serious
outbreak and we will need to work together'." Ms Quin said: "In this
report, it says that there were quite clearly teething troubles during the
initial deployment of the Armed Forces in 1967. I believe that a lot of
these troubles were avoided this time in the preparation that took place
for Army deployment."
Ms Quin said the Government needed to adopt a different approach because
the outbreak this year was not the same. "In the 1967 outbreak, an
absolutely crucial difference is that the farm reported the disease and it
was identified within 4 days. That was not the case this time around where,
when we traced back to the source farm, it was evident that infection had
been there for at least 2 weeks, possibly longer, and in that time, unlike
1967, the disease had entered sheep and one million movements of sheep had
taken place. Therefore we were dealing with something that was very
different. As all the tracings took place of movements, and we could see
the scale of the problem, we brought the Army in."
Ms Quin rejected suggestions that the Government had ignored the advice of
the main report into outbreak of 1967, which said that epidemiologists
should be put on stand-by "from the start, predicting its probable
development and so providing information that would help in formulating
measures to deal with it". Ms Quin said: "Epidemiologists need some
statistics to go on and therefore they cannot begin work on day one of an
outbreak. Epidemiologists were brought in as soon as there were some
statistics."
[Byline: Andrew Sparrow, Political Correspondent
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Following our joint research in 1968-70, LP Smith set up a system for
collaboration in the field between the Meteorological Office and MAFF in
the event of any future FMD outbreak, essentially to predict future and
undiscovered existing outbreaks. This was tested in various MAFF wargames
and actually used in the SVD outbreak, and found to work successfully. It
necessitated only paper & pencil; see 1970 WMO technical Note #113, pp 7-9
& 19-27. Since that time various successful computer models have been
developed -- Gloster's was the first -- and tested, and their results
published. Ms Quin's comment about epidemiologists only able to come late
to FMD outbreaks is not fully informed. They have an important place on the
first day. - Mod.MHJ
***
[3
Date: 7 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Telegraph [edited
<http://www.telegraph.co.uk:80/et?ac=002559874442765&rtmo=lvAow7kt&atmo=tttttttd&pg=/et/01/4/7/nfnm07.html>
Government was warned of epidemic risks last year
----------------------------------------------------------------
The chief veterinary officer was warned last year that immediate slaughter
could cut the impact of a foot and mouth epidemic by more than half. The
ministry also ignored warnings from its own epidemiologist, Prof John
Wilesmith, who was said to be demoralised by the inability of the ministry
to deploy sufficient resources to slaughter animals immediately after
diagnosis of disease.
An internet search yesterday showed that a clear warning was given by
epidemiologists in the October edition of the journal Research in
Veterinary Science. The article by a leading team of epidemiologists who
have since moved from Oxford University to Imperial College, London, was
titled "The Importance Of Immediate Destruction In Epidemics Of Foot And
Mouth Disease." It warned of "serious economic consequences". The team
studied the October 1967 outbreak in Britain and an epidemic in Taiwan in
1997. Using computer simulations, Dr Sally Howard and Dr Christl Donnelly
were able to predict what would have happened if animals in those outbreaks
had all been slaughtered on the day they were diagnosed.
In the 1967 epidemic, the majority of herds were slaughtered on the same
day, but in a small number of cases it took up to 3 days -- the average
delay in the latest epidemic until recently. Had all herds been slaughtered
immediately in 1967, the team concluded that the number of herds infected
in the first 100 days could have been cut from 2127 to 1539.
The Taiwan epidemic is similar to the latest British outbreak. It was
spread rapidly by the movement of animals, and the speed with which it was
stamped out could not compete with new outbreaks, creating long delays in
slaughter and disposal of carcasses. However, the epidemic was confined to
pigs, which breathe out significantly more virus than other animals, and
vaccination was used. Over a month, there were outbreaks in 4385 herds. But
if same-day destruction had been used, the figure would have been cut to
1621 herds. The report said: "Had it been possible to implement this
policy, the epidemic could have been brought under control much sooner and
would have resulted in fewer than half the infected herds ever having been
infected."
The concluding line of the report is chillingly relevant: "The prompt
destruction of infected herds is a well-recognized objective, and whilst
limitations on resources may make it difficult, this work demonstrates the
very high priority that must be given to this control measure."
A Maff spokesman said yesterday: "It has always been known that it is
important to slaughter as quickly as possible. What we have tried to do is
to achieve that."
[Byline: Roger Highfield, Science Editor
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[It is always nice when a team of young scientists confirm the veracity of
what one had written 30 years earlier; see Hugh-Jones & Wright, J. Hygiene
(1970) 68:253-271. If they had asked, it would have been possible to
provide Howard & Donnelly with full individual herd data for the 1967-68
epidemic instead of depending on HMSO summary data. Maybe someone will also
have the foresight this time to archive the data from this epidemic for
studies in 30 years time. - Mod.MHJ
